CellNX\":\"0.0\",\"BloodRNANeutrophilNX\":\"0.5\",\"BloodRNANKCellNX\":\"0.0\",\"BloodRNANonClassicalMonocyteNX\":\"0.0\",\"BloodRNAPlasmacytoidDCNX\":\"0.0\",\"BloodRNATRegNX\":\"0.0\",\"BloodRNATotalPBMCNX\":\"0.0\",\"BrainRNAAmygdalaNX\":\"16.6\",\"BrainRNABasalGangliaNX\":\"20.1\",\"BrainRNACerebellumNX\":\"6.5\",\"BrainRNACerebralCortexNX\":\"32.3\",\"BrainRNAHippocampalFormationNX\":\"13.4\",\"BrainRNAHypothalamusNX\":\"5.4\",\"BrainRNAMidbrainNX\":\"15.8\",\"BrainRNAOlfactoryRegionNX\":\"3.7\",\"BrainRNAPonsAndMedullaNX\":\"19.8\",\"BrainRNAThalamusNX\":\"15.4\"}',NULL,'This gene is a member of the PDGF/VEGF growth factor family. It encodes a heparin-binding protein, which exists as a disulfide-linked homodimer. This growth factor induces proliferation and migration of vascular endothelial cells, and is essential for both physiological and pathological angiogenesis. Disruption of this gene in mice resulted in abnormal embryonic blood vessel formation. This gene is upregulated in many known tumors and its expression is correlated with tumor stage and progression. Elevated levels of this protein are found in patients with POEMS syndrome, also known as Crow-Fukase syndrome. Allelic variants of this gene have been associated with microvascular complications of diabetes 1 (MVCD1) and atherosclerosis. Alternatively spliced transcript variants encoding different isoforms have been described. There is also evidence for alternative translation initiation from upstream non-AUG (CUG) codons resulting in additional isoforms. A recent study showed that a C-terminally extended isoform is produced by use of an alternative in-frame translation termination codon via a stop codon readthrough mechanism, and that this isoform is antiangiogenic. Expression of some isoforms derived from the AUG start codon is regulated by a small upstream open reading frame, which is located within an internal ribosome entry site. [provided by RefSeq, Nov 2015]');
INSERT INTO `gene` VALUES (78,'ABL1','JTK7 c-ABL p150 ABL','ABL proto-oncogene 1, non-receptor tyrosine kinase',25,'ABL1_HUMAN','functional,downstream','9q34.1',130713881,130887675,1,'HS_ABL1_3','NM_007313','NP_009297','108,058,052,065,353,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000','Abl1;Mus musculus,Abl;Drosophila melanogaster,abl-1;Caenorhabditis elegans,Abl1;Rattus norvegicus,abl1;Danio rerio,Abl1;Rattus norvegicus,Abl1;Rattus norvegicus','ABL-киназа консервативна и присутствует у всех многоклеточных [1]. р53, взаимодействующий с ABL, обнаружен у хоанофлагеллят раннего многоклеточного — морского анемона [2]. Более короткие ABL встречаются у заднежгутиковых [3].','ABL — это нерецепторная тирозин-протеин киназа, которая играет роль во многих процессах, связанных с ростом клетки и выживанием, такими как ремоделирование цитоскелета в ответ на внеклеточные стимулы, клеточное движение и адгезия, эндоцитоз рецепторов, аутофагия, ответ на повреждение ДНК и апоптоз [4]. Выполняет важную роль в развитии центральной нервной системы [5 - обзор].','Прямые доказательства на культурах клеток, Ассоциации гена с долголетием/фенотипом старения','Мыши с нокаутом c-ABL имеют фенотип схожий с возрастным остеопорозом [6, 7]. с-ABL стимулирует клеточное старение или ингибирует апоптоз в зависимости от уровня повреждения ДНК [8].','ABL kinase is conserved and present in all metazoan [1]. p53 is an interactor of ABL is found in choanoflagellates early metazoan sea anemone [2]. Shorter ABL are found in opisthokonts [3].','Non-receptor tyrosine-protein kinase that plays a role in many key processes linked to cell growth and survival such as cytoskeleton remodeling in response to extracellular stimuli, cell motility and adhesion, receptor endocytosis, autophagy, DNA damage response and apoptosis [4]. Plays a crucial role in the development of the central nervous system [5 - review].',' c-Abl knockout mice display a phenotype similar to aging-associated osteoporosis [6, 7]. c-ABL appears to promote senescence or inhibit apoptosis, depending on the extent of DNA damage in human cancer cell lines [8].','[1] 10.1126/scisignal.3139re6, [2] 10.1101/cshperspect.a001198, [3] 10.1016/j.febslet.2008.02.002, [4] https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P00519, [5] 10.1007/s12031-011-9588-1, [6] 10.4161/cc.4.2.1490, [7] 10.1038/73542, [8] 10.1016/j.cellsig.2013.10.005',NULL,1,0,NULL,1614611908,3,'','',6,'ENSG00000097007','{\"Gene\":\"ABL1\",\"GeneSynonym\":[\"ABL\",\"c-ABL\",\"JTK7\",\"p150\"],\"Ensembl\":\"ENSG00000097007\",\"GeneDescription\":\"ABL proto-oncogene 1, non-receptor tyrosine kinase\",\"Uniprot\":[\"P00519\"],\"Chromosome\":\"9\",\"Position\":\"130713946-130887675\",\"ProteinClass\":[\"Cancer-related genes\",\"Disease related genes\",\"Enzymes\",\"FDA approved drug targets\",\"Predicted intracellular proteins\",\"RAS pathway related proteins\"],\"BiologicalProcess\":[\"Apoptosis\",\"Autophagy\",\"Cell adhesion\",\"DNA damage\",\"DNA repair\",\"Endocytosis\"],\"MolecularFunction\":[\"DNA-binding\",\"Kinase\",\"Transferase\",\"Tyrosine-protein kinase\"],\"DiseaseInvolvement\":[\"Cancer-related genes\",\"Disease mutation\",\"FDA approved drug targets\",\"Proto-oncogene\"],\"Evidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"HPAEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"UniProtEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"NeXtProtEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"MSEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"RNATissueSpecificity\":\"Low tissue specificity\",\"RNATissueDistribution\":\"Detected in all\",\"RNATissueSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNATissueSpecificNX\":null,\"RNACellLineSpecificity\":\"Low cell line specificity\",\"RNACellLineDistribution\":\"Detected in all\",\"RNACellLineSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNACellLineSpecificNX\":null,\"RNACancerSpecificity\":\"Low cancer specificity\",\"RNACancerDistribution\":\"Detected in all\",\"RNACancerSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNACancerSpecificFPKM\":null,\"RNABrainRegionalSpecificity\":\"Low region specificity\",\"RNABrainRegionalDis