 binds and inactivates members of the transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-beta) superfamily signaling proteins, such as bone morphogenetic protein-4 (BMP4). By diffusing through extracellular matrices more efficiently than members of the TGF-beta superfamily, this protein may have a principal role in creating morphogenic gradients. The protein appears to have pleiotropic effect, both early in development as well as in later stages. It was originally isolated from Xenopus based on its ability to restore normal dorsal-ventral body axis in embryos that had been artificially ventralized by UV treatment. The results of the mouse knockout of the ortholog suggest that it is involved in numerous developmental processes, such as neural tube fusion and joint formation. Recently, several dominant human NOG mutations in unrelated families with proximal symphalangism (SYM1) and multiple synostoses syndrome (SYNS1) were identified; both SYM1 and SYNS1 have multiple joint fusion as their principal feature, and map to the same region (17q22) as this gene. All of these mutations altered evolutionarily conserved amino acid residues. The amino acid sequence of this human gene is highly homologous to that of Xenopus, rat and mouse. [provided by RefSeq, Jul 2008]');
INSERT INTO `gene` VALUES (229,'ELN','WBS WS SVAS','elastin',2006,'ELN_HUMAN','human_link','7q11.23',74027789,74069906,1,'','NM_000501','NP_000492','16,212,450,981,936,300,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000','Eln;Mus musculus,Eln;Rattus norvegicus','Протеин с большим количеством повторов, что делает сложным изучение его филогении. Множество эластинов было изучено у позвоночных животных [1]','Эластин — ключевой протеин внеклеточного матрикса, обладающий эластичностью и упругостью. Участвует в формировании таких тканей, как большие артерии, легкие, связки, кожа, эластичные хрящи, сухожилия [2].','Возрастные изменения экспрессии гена/активности белка у человека, Ассоциации гена с долголетием/фенотипом старения','Очень низкая скорость возобновления эластина в организме ведет к накоплению возрастных изменений, вызванных механическим повреждением, протеолизом, кальцификацией, гликированием [3]. Также было показано, что у людей по мере старения, снижается концентрация эластина в аорте [5]. УФ-радиация может вызывать альтернативный сплайсинг эластина, что впоследствии ведет к неправильной сборке эластиновых тяжей, что является основным признаком фотостарения кожи [4].','Highly repetitive protein, hard to study phylogeny. Many different elastins are found in Vertebrates [1].','Elastin is a key extracellular matrix protein that is critical to the elasticity and resilience of many vertebrate tissues including large arteries, lung, ligament, tendon, skin, and elastic cartilage [2].','The very low turnover rate of elastin in vivo leads to accumulation of age-related changes caused by mechanical fracture, proteolysis and calcification/glycation [3]. UV radiation-induced alternative splicing of the elastin gene, which leads to the inadequate synthesis of the proteins required for the correct assembly of elastic fibers [4]. effect of age on elastin showed that its concentration within the aorta decreased with age [5].','[1] 10.1016/j.matbio.2007.05.005, [2]  10.1016/S0065-3233(05)70013-9, [3] 10.1093/cvr/cvw061, [4] 10.1111/ics.12372, [5] 10.1098/rsif.2012.1004',NULL,1,0,NULL,1614757190,9,'','',4,'ENSG00000049540','{\"Gene\":\"ELN\",\"GeneSynonym\":[\"SVAS\",\"WBS\",\"WS\"],\"Ensembl\":\"ENSG00000049540\",\"GeneDescription\":\"Elastin\",\"Uniprot\":[\"P15502\"],\"Chromosome\":\"7\",\"Position\":\"74027789-74069907\",\"ProteinClass\":[\"Disease related genes\",\"Plasma proteins\",\"Predicted secreted proteins\"],\"BiologicalProcess\":null,\"MolecularFunction\":null,\"DiseaseInvolvement\":[\"Williams-Beuren syndrome\"],\"Evidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"HPAEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"UniProtEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"NeXtProtEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"MSEvidence\":\"Evidence at protein level\",\"RNATissueSpecificity\":\"Low tissue specificity\",\"RNATissueDistribution\":\"Detected in many\",\"RNATissueSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNATissueSpecificNX\":null,\"RNACellLineSpecificity\":\"Cell line enhanced\",\"RNACellLineDistribution\":\"Detected in some\",\"RNACellLineSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNACellLineSpecificNX\":{\"ASCDiff\":\"16.5\",\"BJ\":\"22.9\",\"FHDFTERT166\":\"32.8\",\"U2197\":\"130.7\"},\"RNACancerSpecificity\":\"Low cancer specificity\",\"RNACancerDistribution\":\"Detected in all\",\"RNACancerSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNACancerSpecificFPKM\":null,\"RNABrainRegionalSpecificity\":\"Low region specificity\",\"RNABrainRegionalDistribution\":\"Detected in all\",\"RNABrainRegionalSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNABrainRegionalSpecificNX\":null,\"RNABloodCellSpecificity\":\"Not detected\",\"RNABloodCellDistribution\":\"Not detected\",\"RNABloodCellSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNABloodCellSpecificNX\":null,\"RNABloodLineageSpecificity\":\"Not detected\",\"RNABloodLineageDistribution\":\"Not detected\",\"RNABloodLineageSpecificityScore\":null,\"RNABloodLineageSpecificNX\":null,\"RNAMouseBrainRegionalSpecificity\":\"Low region specificity\",\"RN